1
00:00:01,786 --> 00:00:30,307
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble.

2
00:00:30,557 --> 00:00:32,119
and fully self-enlightened.

3
00:00:34,421 --> 00:00:43,051
Right, tonight I'm going to try to be impossible and try to explain this whole doctrine of not-self.

4
00:00:47,557 --> 00:00:51,521
The Buddha is very clear that there are certain things where language can't reach.

5
00:00:52,563 --> 00:00:58,270
And when we're talking about something which is beyond phenomena, language just won't do.

6
00:00:58,688 --> 00:01:16,149
So if you take, for instance, trying to describe the colour green to somebody who's been blind since birth, and you talk about how it differs from red and grey and yellow, and then you give all sorts of imagery about green valleys and green trees and green leaves.

7
00:01:16,989 --> 00:01:25,118
In the end, the blind person has some idea that green is some sort of colour, but they won't be able to visualise it.

8
00:01:25,780 --> 00:01:28,222
So we have to be very careful about...

9
00:01:28,658 --> 00:01:54,126
conceptual ideas about not-self Buddhism itself began to develop a very intricate metaphysical philosophy begun by somebody who's recognized possibly as the greatest metaphysician in the world, Nagarjuna who went on and on about emptiness and then because trying to get rid of the concept of emptiness

10
00:01:54,427 --> 00:01:56,150
He talks about the emptiness of emptiness.

11
00:01:57,391 --> 00:02:01,257
And that's exactly what language and concepts do.

12
00:02:01,677 --> 00:02:03,019
They fall into themselves.

13
00:02:03,060 --> 00:02:05,703
You're constantly trying to define what you mean.

14
00:02:07,966 --> 00:02:12,332
So with that in mind, we'll have a go at this not-self.

15
00:02:12,353 --> 00:02:20,104
But hopefully at the end of the talk, I'll give you an exercise whereby you can actually begin to experience it.

16
00:02:20,123 --> 00:02:21,986
Some of which we've already talked about.

17
00:02:25,865 --> 00:02:30,312
The next thing is to really understand what was meant by atta.

18
00:02:31,112 --> 00:02:32,735
An atta, not self atta.

19
00:02:32,756 --> 00:02:33,356
What was the atta?

20
00:02:33,978 --> 00:02:38,365
So at the time of the Buddha there was considerable confusion about what this atta was.

21
00:02:39,766 --> 00:02:43,111
And what they were taught is translated in the West as not self.

22
00:02:43,733 --> 00:02:48,621
Which is unfortunate because the word we should use is soul or spirit.

23
00:02:49,722 --> 00:02:51,044
That's what the Buddha is arguing about.

24
00:02:51,185 --> 00:02:53,407
He's arguing about...

25
00:02:53,692 --> 00:02:56,414
Something which people believed was internal.

26
00:02:56,814 --> 00:02:57,556
Well, what was it?

27
00:02:58,417 --> 00:03:07,706
So, how do you describe something which is eternal, doesn't die, is the unconditioned, is not born, not created, and so on?

28
00:03:07,727 --> 00:03:09,909
How do you describe something like that?

29
00:03:09,930 --> 00:03:12,872
So, eventually, you can only describe it by what it isn't.

30
00:03:14,514 --> 00:03:22,804
So, the Buddha simply says, he puts to the early disciples, he puts to them certain questions.

31
00:03:22,969 --> 00:03:24,893
as to is it this or is it that.

32
00:03:25,533 --> 00:03:30,941
So now, what would be the constituents of a soul, of an eternal soul?

33
00:03:33,084 --> 00:03:34,566
Well, the first thing is it can't change.

34
00:03:35,106 --> 00:03:37,129
Because if it changes, it's something different.

35
00:03:38,050 --> 00:03:39,012
So it's not eternal.

36
00:03:39,032 --> 00:03:39,733
It's as simple as that.

37
00:03:40,594 --> 00:03:47,044
If you say, for instance, an emotion, I am happy, and the next minute you're sad, then where's your happiness gone?

38
00:03:47,063 --> 00:03:50,108
You can't be the happiness and the sadness at the same time.

39
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:51,800
So we're talking about being.

40
00:03:51,901 --> 00:03:54,644
We're not talking about something becoming and changing.

41
00:03:55,604 --> 00:04:02,431
So a quality of the soul or spirit is this quality of non-change, unchanging.

42
00:04:03,894 --> 00:04:07,918
The second thing is it can't suffer because it's in control of itself.

43
00:04:08,018 --> 00:04:09,218
It is itself.

44
00:04:10,099 --> 00:04:14,705
And therefore, it can decide, as it were, that it's going to be happy or sad.

45
00:04:15,665 --> 00:04:19,470
If it didn't have that control, then it can't be me.

46
00:04:20,497 --> 00:04:24,762
parents have a certain control over their children.

47
00:04:25,362 --> 00:04:28,045
But they know full well that eventually they have no control.

48
00:04:30,228 --> 00:04:34,192
The control is simply a contract between the child and the parent.

49
00:04:34,973 --> 00:04:37,675
It's something that's imagined between them.

50
00:04:37,696 --> 00:04:45,384
But ultimately, control is part and parcel of the definition of a soul or a self.

51
00:04:45,463 --> 00:04:49,608
If it's not in control of itself, then it means that it can be

52
00:04:49,927 --> 00:05:15,747
changed by circumstance so now one thing the soul can do this eternal soul is it can make itself happy it is in a state of happiness now we have to be careful how we define happiness it's not an emotion because emotions change so we're talking about something which is a state beyond emotional states we'll come to that in a bit

53
00:05:19,254 --> 00:05:43,812
and the final thing is it has to have some sort of substantiality it has to be real so often you get words like the real the ultimate the absolute in all religions you see so there has to be this quality of is-ness it exists

54
00:05:46,576 --> 00:06:13,089
defining that as different from it is becoming if something is becoming then it's stopped being something and it becomes something else so there can't be any change in that process on the other hand it has to be substantial so now the Buddha is saying well okay so we have this definition and he says he's just asking these questions right

55
00:06:13,642 --> 00:06:26,033
So what happens, remember, after he's become fully liberated, he goes back to his companions who don't really want to talk to him because they think he's gone soft, you know, he's left the hard life.

56
00:06:26,935 --> 00:06:30,838
But as he approaches them, they see that something's changed about him.

57
00:06:30,858 --> 00:06:34,641
So I suppose reluctantly they offer him a seat.

58
00:06:36,584 --> 00:06:43,110
And during the ensuing conversation that he has with them, one of the little repetitions that he says is,

59
00:06:43,663 --> 00:06:45,466
have I ever spoken like this before?

60
00:06:45,805 --> 00:06:47,848
Have you ever heard me speak like this before?

61
00:06:49,449 --> 00:06:58,298
Now, the first discourse, as it's put, the turning of the wheel of the law, is obviously a later creation, just laying the platform of his teaching.

62
00:06:59,180 --> 00:07:01,422
But it would have been in this conversational style.

63
00:07:01,923 --> 00:07:11,713
And in the second discourse, they all go off, sorry, then they go off on an arms round, and when they come back and eat and have a rest, he gives them this second talk.

64
00:07:12,283 --> 00:07:15,067
And the second talk is called the Anattalakana Sutta.

65
00:07:15,648 --> 00:07:18,492
It's the discourse on this characteristic of not-self.

66
00:07:19,653 --> 00:07:30,225
And in this discourse, we do get the sense of this conversational process, like this Socratic process that you get in Plato.

67
00:07:30,867 --> 00:07:36,012
Not that I've read Plato, but that's what we mean by this Socratic method of questions and answers.

68
00:07:37,213 --> 00:07:41,059
So I'm going to use this discourse as a sort of basis.

69
00:07:43,047 --> 00:08:12,160
by the way these lovely little e-readers and recorders are actually wonderful I've got a whole library in here so he says you see these discourses always start off with thus have I heard because they were related after his passing by his companion Ananda so it's what Ananda heard on one occasion the blessed one was dwelling at Baranasi in the deer park at Isipatana

70
00:08:12,341 --> 00:08:16,026
So this is where he went to find out where his people were.

71
00:08:16,605 --> 00:08:27,677
If you take the mileage from Bodh Gaya, where he was enlightened, all the way to Varanasi on the Ganges, I sort of remember it as being something like 400 miles.

72
00:08:28,658 --> 00:08:33,384
So his decision to teach really meant that he was on the road.

73
00:08:33,845 --> 00:08:35,666
And he spent the rest of his life on the road, really.

74
00:08:38,089 --> 00:08:40,932
And there the Blessed One addressed the monks.

75
00:08:41,671 --> 00:08:45,717
Monks here means any listener, really.

76
00:08:47,059 --> 00:08:53,451
So they replied, Venerable Sir, now, form is non-self, not self.

77
00:08:55,553 --> 00:08:58,538
Now, the word form refers to our physicality.

78
00:08:59,681 --> 00:09:04,990
And the Buddha gives us a cross-section of the human being in time.

79
00:09:05,471 --> 00:09:06,952
So if you were to stop time,

80
00:09:07,134 --> 00:09:19,716
a human being at this moment, and tried to describe what a psychophysical organism was, he put it in these five aggregates, these five heaps, because he wants to show where the problem lies.

81
00:09:20,015 --> 00:09:23,542
So the first heap is all this physicality.

82
00:09:23,562 --> 00:09:26,267
The second one is our feelings.

83
00:09:27,269 --> 00:09:31,775
All the feelings in the body, both caused by the body itself and by the mind.

84
00:09:42,134 --> 00:09:49,604
The next one is all our perceptions which includes both basic perceptions but it grows into concepts.

85
00:09:50,806 --> 00:09:53,690
They grow into ways of looking at something.

86
00:09:55,532 --> 00:10:00,097
You might include in that both our memory but feeling also has memory too.

87
00:10:01,980 --> 00:10:04,063
Then there's volitional formations.

88
00:10:04,403 --> 00:10:07,467
These are our habits and they are created by acts of will.

89
00:10:08,288 --> 00:10:10,993
And then finally there are acts of cognitions.

90
00:10:12,307 --> 00:10:14,870
All of this must be put on a screen for us to know.

91
00:10:15,251 --> 00:10:17,674
If it's not on a screen we won't be able to see it.

92
00:10:18,836 --> 00:10:22,283
We don't see things when we fall asleep because the screen's sort of fallen.

93
00:10:22,482 --> 00:10:32,578
But there's still stuff coming in and every so often you'll hear something tinkling and it'll wake up this act of cognition and you'll know it's time to get up.

94
00:10:34,942 --> 00:10:40,490
So these are the five components as the Buddha saw it of

95
00:10:41,551 --> 00:10:42,192
the human being.

96
00:10:43,072 --> 00:10:50,019
So physical form is physicality and all the rest is mentality.

97
00:10:50,139 --> 00:11:07,177
The feelings as he experiences them in the body, all the perceptions that they have, which includes more detailed concepts in time, all the habits that we have, both good and bad, driven by, created by the will, and finally these acts of cognition.

98
00:11:08,820 --> 00:11:10,782
I try not to use the word consciousness because

99
00:11:11,032 --> 00:11:12,333
It's being studied these days.

100
00:11:13,174 --> 00:11:19,924
And from a Buddhist point of view, enormous confusion as to what consciousness is.

101
00:11:20,505 --> 00:11:25,673
Some philosophers and some scientists actually think that the content of consciousness is consciousness itself.

102
00:11:25,933 --> 00:11:27,296
Anyway, we don't want to get into that.

103
00:11:27,596 --> 00:11:29,519
So I shall leave that word aside.

104
00:11:29,818 --> 00:11:34,726
Cognition is like on a TV screen, right?

105
00:11:34,746 --> 00:11:39,874
You've got all these...

106
00:11:40,174 --> 00:11:41,616
What is it that hits the TV?

107
00:11:41,636 --> 00:11:43,118
I've forgotten the word for it.

108
00:11:43,138 --> 00:11:44,139
You know, it's hitting the screen.

109
00:11:44,379 --> 00:11:47,583
What are those little subatomic particles that create the light?

110
00:11:47,943 --> 00:11:48,264
Anyway.

111
00:11:50,567 --> 00:11:52,149
Well, it's electrons, isn't it?

112
00:11:52,489 --> 00:11:53,389
I can't remember what it is.

113
00:11:53,409 --> 00:11:58,777
Anyway, the screen on the television manifests, right?

114
00:11:58,836 --> 00:12:01,119
It brings it into a manifest which you can see.

115
00:12:01,679 --> 00:12:05,024
So without that, the TV's useless, eh?

116
00:12:05,043 --> 00:12:06,446
So that's the act of cognition.

117
00:12:06,706 --> 00:12:07,667
There's something in

118
00:12:07,933 --> 00:12:11,097
this brain-mind complex which creates a picture for us.

119
00:12:14,881 --> 00:12:23,530
Those of you who've seen how the eye works when it looks at a picture, it's darting all over the place, completely unknown to us.

120
00:12:23,991 --> 00:12:25,413
What we see is the full picture.

121
00:12:26,153 --> 00:12:29,918
But the eye is constantly moving, picking up little bits and bobs.

122
00:12:30,960 --> 00:12:35,043
But the mind is able to take all that and present us with something that's still.

123
00:12:35,644 --> 00:12:37,366
It gives us an impression of wholeness.

124
00:12:39,236 --> 00:12:44,966
So, when it comes to this not-self, see, this is what he says.

125
00:12:45,047 --> 00:12:56,686
He says, if form, the body, were self, this form, I'm using the word self here, perhaps I should be consistent and say soul.

126
00:12:57,386 --> 00:13:00,873
If form were soul, this form would not lead to affliction.

127
00:13:02,294 --> 00:13:06,020
And it would be possible to determine the body.

128
00:13:06,304 --> 00:13:09,528
let my body be thus, let my body not be thus.

129
00:13:09,687 --> 00:13:19,238
But because the body is not self, is not the soul, not in charge, this form leads to affliction.

130
00:13:19,398 --> 00:13:21,080
This body leads to affliction.

131
00:13:21,100 --> 00:13:24,663
And it is not possible to determine our form.

132
00:13:25,464 --> 00:13:27,525
So we have minimal control over the body.

133
00:13:27,745 --> 00:13:36,294
I can wave my arm around here while I'm speaking and all that, but I can't stop it falling ill, I can't stop it getting older, and I can't stop it dropping dead

134
00:13:36,916 --> 00:13:48,768
So this control I have over my body is a way of saying that whatever soul is, is not the body.

135
00:13:49,068 --> 00:13:49,389
Feeling.

136
00:13:50,490 --> 00:13:56,375
When we discuss feeling from this point of view, we see that we don't have much control over feeling.

137
00:13:57,216 --> 00:13:59,519
When you put your foot on the ground, it feels.

138
00:14:00,581 --> 00:14:03,443
You can't say to your foot, don't feel the footstep.

139
00:14:03,464 --> 00:14:04,585
It'll just simply do it.

140
00:14:04,705 --> 00:14:05,826
We don't have that control.

141
00:14:06,784 --> 00:14:07,765
Same with emotions.

142
00:14:07,885 --> 00:14:11,769
If you get angry over something, you can't stop your body feeling hot.

143
00:14:12,009 --> 00:14:12,971
That's the way it reacts.

144
00:14:13,392 --> 00:14:14,832
If you feel happy, it feels light.

145
00:14:16,375 --> 00:14:21,659
So again, it's to do with looking at feelings and knowing that, well, this can't be a soul.

146
00:14:22,341 --> 00:14:23,061
It can't be eternal.

147
00:14:24,962 --> 00:14:25,604
Perceptions.

148
00:14:26,124 --> 00:14:32,890
Perceptions are changing even more quickly because every time we look at something that we know, it's ever so slightly changed.

149
00:14:33,191 --> 00:14:34,732
So every time you look at a tree,

150
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,182
It's always refining your idea of a tree.

151
00:14:37,802 --> 00:14:43,226
Every time you see a cat, it comes on to the concept of a cat so that you can see, well, this is a cat.

152
00:14:44,048 --> 00:14:47,932
But by looking at that cat, your concept of a cat will slightly change.

153
00:14:48,672 --> 00:14:49,493
It's always changing.

154
00:14:49,673 --> 00:14:58,041
So perceptions, which are manifest in our words and images, are constantly in the process of renewal or forgetting.

155
00:14:58,181 --> 00:14:59,682
You forget things that you knew.

156
00:15:00,643 --> 00:15:02,965
So again, when it comes to control,

157
00:15:04,514 --> 00:15:07,397
our control is minimal.

158
00:15:07,417 --> 00:15:09,980
Then we have these volitional formations, habits.

159
00:15:10,480 --> 00:15:12,903
Well, these are created by acts of will.

160
00:15:13,283 --> 00:15:17,048
So often we have a habit that we might not want.

161
00:15:17,428 --> 00:15:19,951
Say, like a smoker doesn't want to smoke anymore.

162
00:15:19,971 --> 00:15:22,673
That's a habit, so they have to work against the habit.

163
00:15:22,693 --> 00:15:29,201
If they weren't able to change the habit, then of course they would have no control whatsoever.

164
00:15:29,701 --> 00:15:32,125
But what we find is that habits have

165
00:15:32,846 --> 00:15:34,448
an inner strength in themselves.

166
00:15:34,528 --> 00:15:37,552
Trying to get rid of a habit takes time.

167
00:15:38,091 --> 00:15:39,793
And the kernel of it is always there.

168
00:15:40,195 --> 00:15:47,182
So often you hear stories of people who have not smoked for years.

169
00:15:47,822 --> 00:15:48,822
And then they retire.

170
00:15:49,403 --> 00:15:52,466
And at a party, they think, oh, I'll just take the one.

171
00:15:53,148 --> 00:16:01,976
And of course, what they've done is they've kick-started this potential within them of enjoying a cigarette, of enjoying nicotine.

172
00:16:02,918 --> 00:16:04,460
And then they find it difficult to stop.

173
00:16:05,921 --> 00:16:18,234
So even though we've kicked a habit which we felt has dominated us for a while, the potential is always there, you see, as a little kernel, a little seed.

174
00:16:22,197 --> 00:16:23,938
And then finally these acts of cognition.

175
00:16:24,100 --> 00:16:27,842
So acts of cognition happen quite naturally.

176
00:16:27,964 --> 00:16:30,586
As soon as you place your eye on something, you see it.

177
00:16:30,966 --> 00:16:31,407
You can't

178
00:16:31,792 --> 00:16:32,952
You can't not see it.

179
00:16:33,673 --> 00:16:37,599
As soon as a sound comes at your eardrum, you hear it.

180
00:16:37,798 --> 00:16:38,980
You can't not hear it.

181
00:16:40,162 --> 00:16:43,885
You can't decide, well, I won't listen to that because it's already happened.

182
00:16:46,589 --> 00:17:01,647
So, at this basic level of control, we find that if we define a soul, an eternal soul, as something which is in control of itself, then we find that this psychophysical organism doesn't

183
00:17:01,929 --> 00:17:06,214
Doesn't live up to it.

184
00:17:06,234 --> 00:17:08,377
Then you get this question and answer business.

185
00:17:08,798 --> 00:17:11,761
So now he's going on to the quality of impermanence.

186
00:17:11,781 --> 00:17:13,865
So he says, what do you think?

187
00:17:14,506 --> 00:17:16,888
Is form, is the body permanent or impermanent?

188
00:17:17,589 --> 00:17:18,851
Impermanent, venerable sir.

189
00:17:19,011 --> 00:17:21,255
You're very good at these ones.

190
00:17:21,275 --> 00:17:23,778
Is what is impermanent suffering or happiness?

191
00:17:24,699 --> 00:17:28,182
Oh, suffering, sir.

192
00:17:28,202 --> 00:17:31,126
Is what is impermanent suffering and subject to change

193
00:17:31,444 --> 00:17:37,551
fit to be regarded as, this is mine, this I am, this is myself.

194
00:17:37,571 --> 00:17:39,713
So here we have three relationships.

195
00:17:41,155 --> 00:17:42,037
Something that I own.

196
00:17:43,598 --> 00:17:44,740
Something that I own.

197
00:17:45,881 --> 00:17:46,842
Now think about it.

198
00:17:47,963 --> 00:17:51,948
When you say, this is mine, what are we actually saying?

199
00:17:53,549 --> 00:17:58,776
So when I, like this e-reader you see, Kindle, this is mine.

200
00:17:59,757 --> 00:17:59,876
Right?

201
00:17:59,896 --> 00:18:00,017
Right?

202
00:18:02,241 --> 00:18:05,346
And I'm very attached to it, by the way.

203
00:18:07,410 --> 00:18:11,176
Somebody comes along and sees my Kindle and decides they want it.

204
00:18:11,998 --> 00:18:12,999
So they take my Kindle.

205
00:18:14,080 --> 00:18:16,184
Now I go around saying, somebody stole my Kindle.

206
00:18:16,244 --> 00:18:17,646
Somebody's taken my Kindle.

207
00:18:18,268 --> 00:18:19,048
It's not mine, is it?

208
00:18:19,529 --> 00:18:20,111
It's the thief's.

209
00:18:20,151 --> 00:18:20,771
The thief's got it.

210
00:18:21,212 --> 00:18:21,814
It's his Kindle.

211
00:18:24,278 --> 00:18:27,522
So this, my business, is just a legal fiction.

212
00:18:28,448 --> 00:18:31,811
It's just something we've made up in society concerning my-ness.

213
00:18:32,813 --> 00:18:33,413
This is mine.

214
00:18:34,414 --> 00:18:37,178
What we come to understand is when it comes to objects, you can only use them.

215
00:18:37,858 --> 00:18:39,941
As soon as you start possessing them, you end up suffering.

216
00:18:41,343 --> 00:18:42,544
The potential for suffering.

217
00:18:45,346 --> 00:18:46,008
This I am.

218
00:18:46,028 --> 00:18:55,137
So now, if you pose yourself a question, if you pose this little sentence, I am, and finish it off.

219
00:18:57,340 --> 00:18:58,422
So, I am

220
00:18:58,688 --> 00:18:59,249
A nurse.

221
00:19:00,349 --> 00:19:01,632
I am a teacher.

222
00:19:02,613 --> 00:19:02,893
I am.

223
00:19:04,515 --> 00:19:05,656
Is that permanent?

224
00:19:05,676 --> 00:19:08,180
This I am is always having to describe itself.

225
00:19:08,240 --> 00:19:09,741
It's always self-referential.

226
00:19:10,603 --> 00:19:14,708
If you say I am happy, where does the I go when you're unhappy?

227
00:19:18,073 --> 00:19:20,736
So this I am is always a definition.

228
00:19:21,656 --> 00:19:25,422
It's always you have to finish the sentence and then you realise that

229
00:19:26,026 --> 00:19:33,561
This I is only a way of describing what there is being done at any given moment.

230
00:19:33,582 --> 00:19:36,387
So if you're teaching, yes, I am teaching.

231
00:19:36,407 --> 00:19:37,590
But is there a teacher there?

232
00:19:39,654 --> 00:19:45,047
If the teacher is being created by the sense of I, what's actually happening is the process of teaching.

233
00:19:50,443 --> 00:19:52,486
And then finally, my self or my soul.

234
00:19:53,267 --> 00:19:56,750
Remember, when we talk about self, we talk about soul, something eternal.

235
00:19:56,769 --> 00:19:59,653
So can we say that about the body?

236
00:20:02,154 --> 00:20:02,214
No.

237
00:20:02,234 --> 00:20:03,797
I hope you agree with me.

238
00:20:03,817 --> 00:20:05,557
So then he goes on to the other parts.

239
00:20:05,617 --> 00:20:08,181
So feeling, is it permanent or impermanent?

240
00:20:10,103 --> 00:20:12,545
Perceptions, are they permanent or impermanent?

241
00:20:13,506 --> 00:20:17,829
Our volitional formations, these habits that we have, are they permanent or impermanent?

242
00:20:18,451 --> 00:20:20,011
And are these acts of cognition?

243
00:20:21,173 --> 00:20:22,534
Are they permanent or impermanent?

244
00:20:22,934 --> 00:20:26,238
So the answer, of course, is they're all impermanent, venerable sir.

245
00:20:27,159 --> 00:20:30,021
And is what is impermanent suffering or happiness?

246
00:20:30,261 --> 00:20:32,545
Well, it's unsatisfactory, isn't it?

247
00:20:32,565 --> 00:20:37,369
Now, why is it that these things are unsatisfactory?

248
00:20:37,390 --> 00:20:42,674
It's because we're searching always for that complete, utter happiness and contentment.

249
00:20:43,175 --> 00:20:44,237
It's within us to do that.

250
00:20:45,317 --> 00:20:49,442
As a human being, we find ourselves in a constant surge

251
00:20:49,777 --> 00:21:19,445
of trying to be happy however you wish to define it you might be happy with a lot of money might be happy with a lot of friends it doesn't matter how we define it but we always want to be happy and contented but because as soon as we get something which we say is happy and then we finally come to a point in our lives and we say oh now I've got everything I wanted as soon as you've said that it's gone you want to stop the world

252
00:21:19,712 --> 00:21:21,615
Now I've got it.

253
00:21:23,096 --> 00:21:26,538
But the very grasping of that moment undermines its joy.

254
00:21:31,683 --> 00:21:35,307
To kiss a joy as it flies is to live in eternity's sunrise.

255
00:21:35,646 --> 00:21:35,968
Blake.

256
00:21:37,909 --> 00:21:38,710
But we don't want to do that.

257
00:21:38,730 --> 00:21:39,330
We want to catch it.

258
00:21:46,297 --> 00:21:47,678
So what is impermanence?

259
00:21:47,978 --> 00:21:51,142
Is suffering subject to change?

260
00:21:51,982 --> 00:21:57,450
Is what is impermanent and unsatisfactory and subject to change?

261
00:21:58,711 --> 00:22:00,634
Should we regard it as this is mine?

262
00:22:02,896 --> 00:22:09,365
Should I become attached to things when I know that there's potential for unsatisfactoriness there?

263
00:22:09,384 --> 00:22:10,886
Sometimes great suffering.

264
00:22:13,450 --> 00:22:16,713
This gets very difficult when you start talking about relationships.

265
00:22:16,733 --> 00:22:17,714
How can you love

266
00:22:18,134 --> 00:22:45,525
without the attachment this I am see a self definition as soon as you say that and it's undermined then you're into some form of suffering and this is my real this is my soul this is my eternal self well that's difficult so then he tries to put all this together therefore any kind of form that's the body remember

267
00:22:46,096 --> 00:22:53,644
Whatsoever, whether past, future or present, internal or external, gross, subtle, inferior or superior, far or near.

268
00:22:54,266 --> 00:22:55,507
See, he's trying to cover all angles.

269
00:22:57,348 --> 00:23:03,395
All bodies, all physical natures should be seen as they really are with the correct understanding.

270
00:23:04,237 --> 00:23:05,238
This is not mine.

271
00:23:06,619 --> 00:23:07,500
This is not me.

272
00:23:07,520 --> 00:23:08,602
This is I am not.

273
00:23:08,782 --> 00:23:12,487
And this is not a soul or a self.

274
00:23:12,507 --> 00:23:15,951
And then of course he says that of the other four heaps.

275
00:23:16,588 --> 00:23:25,701
the feelings, all the feelings that we have, all the perceptions, all the different habits that we collect, and our acts of cognition.

276
00:23:28,204 --> 00:23:37,498
Then he says, when we see this, when we really grasp this, the instructed noble disciple becomes disenchanted with the body.

277
00:23:39,961 --> 00:23:40,843
Disenchanted.

278
00:23:41,083 --> 00:23:44,587
So, what does enchantment mean, you see?

279
00:23:44,737 --> 00:23:47,441
It's caught up in a dream, caught up in a fantasy.

280
00:23:49,304 --> 00:23:53,289
So just to break that fantasy, break the dream, you see.

281
00:23:56,654 --> 00:24:08,152
And disenchanted with feeling, disenchanted with perception, disenchanted with habits, volitional formations, and disenchanted with acts of cognition.

282
00:24:08,271 --> 00:24:11,376
And becoming disenchanted, it becomes dispassionate.

283
00:24:12,479 --> 00:24:13,359
Now that sounds...

284
00:24:14,048 --> 00:24:20,176
That sounds sort of empty, you know, like what happens if you've no passion, if you've no emotions?

285
00:24:21,739 --> 00:24:26,445
So remember, these are the emotions that he's talking about driven by wrong understanding.

286
00:24:27,547 --> 00:24:28,769
This is not the Buddha heart.

287
00:24:29,109 --> 00:24:35,578
The Buddha heart is full of love, compassion, sympathetic joy, peacefulness, and all the things that we love.

288
00:24:36,621 --> 00:24:41,827
But what he's talking about here are all those mental states that are driven by this sense of self.

289
00:24:43,208 --> 00:24:48,718
It even corrupts things like love because love slips into its near enemy of attachment.

290
00:24:49,618 --> 00:24:54,347
It corrupts compassion because it slips into its near enemy, its subtle enemy of grief.

291
00:24:56,111 --> 00:24:59,737
It corrupts joy into excitement, over excitement.

292
00:25:01,079 --> 00:25:02,942
And equanimity slips into indifference.

293
00:25:03,423 --> 00:25:08,051
It's all done because we're not actually seeing things, in his terms, as they really are.

294
00:25:11,592 --> 00:25:17,680
Now it's through this undermining of this wrong relationship that finally somebody comes to be liberated.

295
00:25:18,461 --> 00:25:20,002
And then that person understands.

296
00:25:21,384 --> 00:25:22,467
Destroyed his birth.

297
00:25:24,068 --> 00:25:25,912
The spiritual life has been lived.

298
00:25:27,093 --> 00:25:29,016
What had to be done has been done.

299
00:25:30,257 --> 00:25:33,121
Lovely sense of completion there.

300
00:25:33,141 --> 00:25:36,385
There is no more coming back into any state of becoming.

301
00:25:37,647 --> 00:25:37,988
Now.

302
00:25:38,457 --> 00:25:41,661
When the Buddha became fully liberated, he did not disappear.

303
00:25:42,402 --> 00:25:48,107
Nor did he become a sort of amorphous blob by the side of the road with a sign saying, Liberated.

304
00:25:48,909 --> 00:25:49,630
Do not disturb.

305
00:25:49,670 --> 00:25:56,719
From other people's point of view, his personality was the same.

306
00:25:58,019 --> 00:25:58,780
He looked the same.

307
00:25:59,261 --> 00:26:01,584
Visually outside, nothing had happened.

308
00:26:02,105 --> 00:26:04,948
But internally, something had changed.

309
00:26:05,808 --> 00:26:07,991
And what had changed was that sense of me

310
00:26:08,443 --> 00:26:11,607
So what he's talking about is the rebirthing of me.

311
00:26:12,449 --> 00:26:16,214
The rebirthing of a wrong sense of self.

312
00:26:16,234 --> 00:26:17,276
That's what disappears.

313
00:26:21,701 --> 00:26:28,010
Now when the Blessed One had spoken this elated those monks delighted in the Buddha's statement.

314
00:26:29,492 --> 00:26:37,624
And while this discourse was being spoken the minds of the monks of the group of five these were his five early companions were liberated

315
00:26:38,009 --> 00:26:41,615
From the taints of non-clinging.

316
00:26:42,536 --> 00:26:43,978
We're all liberated right then and there.

317
00:26:45,760 --> 00:26:46,301
Anybody here?

318
00:26:50,449 --> 00:26:50,628
No?

319
00:26:50,648 --> 00:26:51,109
Go and ask her.

320
00:26:53,753 --> 00:26:57,199
So we have here a very clear exposition.

321
00:26:57,460 --> 00:26:59,462
And none of it, you see, is philosophy.

322
00:27:00,545 --> 00:27:01,425
None of it is philosophy.

323
00:27:01,826 --> 00:27:02,847
You have to think about it.

324
00:27:03,148 --> 00:27:05,231
You have to experience it for yourself.

325
00:27:08,012 --> 00:27:16,203
Now, he gives this description of not-self in this cross-section of time.

326
00:27:16,224 --> 00:27:21,291
If you were to take a human being in the present moment, you would end up with these five categories.

327
00:27:21,311 --> 00:27:26,719
But he also takes a human being and sees it in a process that we call dependent origination.

328
00:27:27,921 --> 00:27:35,151
And there's not the time to go into that deeply, but what he points out in that process is that

329
00:27:36,193 --> 00:27:39,076
The sense of I comes late in the process.

330
00:27:40,699 --> 00:27:42,260
First of all, there is contact.

331
00:27:43,721 --> 00:27:56,096
Then when there's a contact with something, there arises a definition of it in terms of its, as the books say, hedonic value, which means whether it's pleasant or unpleasant.

332
00:27:56,896 --> 00:28:00,661
We decide whether it's pleasant or unpleasant, or a shade of that.

333
00:28:00,681 --> 00:28:03,223
Once that's decided, we form a relationship to it.

334
00:28:03,243 --> 00:28:04,986
We either want it or we don't want it,

335
00:28:06,231 --> 00:28:08,713
And it's only then that the sense of I comes.

336
00:28:09,694 --> 00:28:27,413
So in our language, we will say, I will get this nice ice cream which I've seen in the shop.

337
00:28:27,432 --> 00:28:32,377
I will get the nice ice cream which I saw in the shop.

338
00:28:32,397 --> 00:28:34,720
Psychologically, what's happening is the other way around.

339
00:28:35,999 --> 00:28:38,922
See, I scream in the shop.

340
00:28:38,942 --> 00:28:43,026
Like, get, sorry, I, get.

341
00:28:43,906 --> 00:28:53,016
The I, the sense of I, comes quite late in that process of recognising something and deciding to do something.

342
00:28:55,117 --> 00:28:56,900
So the I is not always there.

343
00:28:57,840 --> 00:29:04,807
But because the mind is moving at such terrific speed, we get this sense of a constant me in that process.

344
00:29:07,285 --> 00:29:36,549
these neurobiologists have done tests to show that decisions are made before the person knows them and then as it were agrees to it but the person actually believes they've made that decision now in Buddhist terms that's called the unaware life because one of the things we're doing on a retreat is being aware of our intentions

345
00:29:37,406 --> 00:29:46,338
When you're aware of your intentions, then you re-empower yourself to take power over your life, to take control of your life.

346
00:29:46,358 --> 00:29:47,500
Because then you decide.

347
00:29:47,519 --> 00:29:55,631
But when we're living at an automated level, you're just behaving on a habitual level.

348
00:29:56,171 --> 00:30:01,298
But then we do this little trick where we think that actually we've made the decision.

349
00:30:03,461 --> 00:30:06,704
So you walk down the aisle with all these hundreds of biscuits.

350
00:30:07,157 --> 00:30:08,759
thinking that you're going to have a choice.

351
00:30:09,819 --> 00:30:11,582
But you end up buying the chocolate biscuits.

352
00:30:13,423 --> 00:30:17,086
And then you say to yourself, well, I decided to buy these chocolate biscuits.

353
00:30:17,106 --> 00:30:17,428
Phooey.

354
00:30:18,268 --> 00:30:18,729
What a rubbish.

355
00:30:21,811 --> 00:30:26,955
It's only when you make the process conscious to yourself that you can then make an informed decision.

356
00:30:29,638 --> 00:30:32,721
So that's dependence origination.

357
00:30:32,741 --> 00:30:35,765
Now, how do we approach this?

358
00:30:35,865 --> 00:30:36,085
Okay.

359
00:30:36,352 --> 00:30:44,538
So let's take a more modern approach in the sense of what happens to us from the point of in the womb onwards.

360
00:30:45,420 --> 00:30:54,647
So somewhere in the womb it seems as though we slowly become aware of what's around us.

361
00:30:54,847 --> 00:30:55,989
We don't know it's around us.

362
00:30:56,048 --> 00:30:57,089
We feel it's in us.

363
00:30:57,210 --> 00:30:58,050
We feel it is us.

364
00:30:58,431 --> 00:30:59,913
But we can hear our mother's voice.

365
00:31:01,294 --> 00:31:03,476
We can sense her moods and so on.

366
00:31:03,496 --> 00:31:04,997
This is what they say.

367
00:31:05,017 --> 00:31:05,817
Then we're born

368
00:31:06,523 --> 00:31:15,778
And it would seem that for the first three or four months, we just live in this bath of stimulus, which has no depth to it.

369
00:31:15,857 --> 00:31:17,079
It's like a kaleidoscope.

370
00:31:17,339 --> 00:31:20,243
All we know is when it hurts and when it doesn't hurt.

371
00:31:20,605 --> 00:31:21,666
And when it hurts, we scream.

372
00:31:22,307 --> 00:31:24,270
When it doesn't hurt, we feel okay.

373
00:31:24,310 --> 00:31:32,803
Somewhere within that mass, it seems, after about three or four months, the first object looms out of it.

374
00:31:33,924 --> 00:31:35,426
And for the most part, of course, it's our mothers.

375
00:31:35,728 --> 00:31:36,008
So...

376
00:31:36,307 --> 00:31:37,910
There's some separation going on.

377
00:31:38,611 --> 00:31:46,880
And it would seem that when a child, when a baby is lunging out in the pram for its baubles and bangles, it's actually creating a 3D world.

378
00:31:47,279 --> 00:31:49,482
It doesn't exist until they've actually created it.

379
00:31:51,945 --> 00:31:59,354
Now, you can see that what the baby's doing is pushing the outside world outward from its sense of self.

380
00:32:00,194 --> 00:32:02,617
It does because it doesn't have a conceptual idea of itself.

381
00:32:02,738 --> 00:32:05,421
It just experiences everything as itself.

382
00:32:06,785 --> 00:32:16,116
As it pushes everything out, somewhere along the line, I don't know how old the child is, probably at the point where it becomes self-aware, which, I don't know, somewhere around about the age of one and a half, is it?

383
00:32:17,057 --> 00:32:17,858
Perhaps a little earlier.

384
00:32:19,080 --> 00:32:23,747
I think chimpanzees get there by the age of three, don't they?

385
00:32:23,767 --> 00:32:35,001
So finally, this little baby has pushed the world out and is becoming quite clear that the world is out there and I'm in it.

386
00:32:35,481 --> 00:32:36,083
This is me.

387
00:32:36,703 --> 00:32:41,671
And usually somewhere along the line, perhaps, I don't know, before three, I ought to read this stuff to get it clear.

388
00:32:42,592 --> 00:32:44,335
The child knows they're a boy or a girl.

389
00:32:44,996 --> 00:32:49,742
And they're quite clear about who and what they are and what they are not.

390
00:32:50,663 --> 00:32:51,986
So this is not me.

391
00:32:52,767 --> 00:32:53,488
Not.

392
00:32:53,508 --> 00:32:55,990
They've got lots of mine, but it's not me.

393
00:32:58,174 --> 00:33:00,438
Now, in our meditation, that's all we're doing.

394
00:33:00,698 --> 00:33:04,163
We're taking that process inward to make outward

395
00:33:04,732 --> 00:33:12,142
To push away from this sense of self what we've always presumed to be me.

396
00:33:12,162 --> 00:33:22,815
As soon as a pain comes in the body, you see, normally speaking, a person might say, oh, I've got pain, you know, and then take an aspirin or something, or shake their leg about it.

397
00:33:22,835 --> 00:33:23,615
But we don't do that.

398
00:33:23,675 --> 00:33:24,576
We sit with it.

399
00:33:24,696 --> 00:33:25,377
We observe it.

400
00:33:26,278 --> 00:33:29,823
And these noting words are very good at making it quite a distance.

401
00:33:29,844 --> 00:33:30,924
So I'm saying, pain, pain.

402
00:33:31,345 --> 00:33:34,368
I can make it more obvious to myself by saying, there

403
00:33:34,888 --> 00:33:38,692
there's pain, there's pleasure, there's a sense of comfort.

404
00:33:39,934 --> 00:33:48,964
And by doing that, I'm relocating my sense of self into that which is observing, which is feeling.

405
00:33:49,025 --> 00:33:55,051
Now that's the easy one.

406
00:33:55,833 --> 00:34:02,500
It gets a little harder when it comes to emotions, because we identify with emotions in a more inward way.

407
00:34:03,559 --> 00:34:09,025
So I'm sitting here and somebody coughs just about when I was going to be fully liberated.

408
00:34:10,007 --> 00:34:11,469
And a great irritation arises.

409
00:34:12,010 --> 00:34:15,813
But I'm quick enough to sit there and observe this feeling of irritation.

410
00:34:16,373 --> 00:34:16,974
What have I done?

411
00:34:17,576 --> 00:34:19,358
I've pushed it away from my sense of me.

412
00:34:20,298 --> 00:34:22,702
I'm saying irritation, there, there.

413
00:34:24,403 --> 00:34:29,710
I hear a bird and the sound of the bird's voice raises joy in me.

414
00:34:30,170 --> 00:34:32,773
And I say joy, there's joy, there's joy.

415
00:34:33,394 --> 00:34:34,757
See?

416
00:34:34,777 --> 00:34:40,985
In so doing, I'm pushing away this sense of me within the joy, making joy an object.

417
00:34:42,146 --> 00:34:47,875
And this sense of me now relocates to that which is feeling and knowing.

418
00:34:51,079 --> 00:34:54,103
When it comes to images in the mind, right?

419
00:34:54,123 --> 00:34:58,369
A big image, sometimes people get colours or strong images in the mind.

420
00:34:59,331 --> 00:35:00,353
You're there, you can see it.

421
00:35:00,853 --> 00:35:01,815
You're looking at it.

422
00:35:02,791 --> 00:35:05,695
You can say imagining, imagining.

423
00:35:05,715 --> 00:35:13,605
And in so doing, again, you've pushed out into an objective, an inner objective world, what was before you thought was me.

424
00:35:14,527 --> 00:35:21,175
And again, the sense of identity is falling back into the observer, the feeler, the knower.

425
00:35:24,579 --> 00:35:26,882
To do that with thought, you've really got to be quite awake.

426
00:35:27,423 --> 00:35:31,548
But you can actually, with good concentration, good attention,

427
00:35:31,900 --> 00:35:36,166
You can see a thought arising and passing away, like a neon light.

428
00:35:37,969 --> 00:35:48,485
So then you're left now, within yourself, with a sense, a strong sense of, I am the observer, a feeler, the one who knows inside ourselves.

429
00:35:50,949 --> 00:35:52,371
And you've pushed everything out, you see.

430
00:35:52,771 --> 00:35:59,882
So everything you've done unwittingly, you see, you've actually said, this is not me, this is not a soul, this is not self,

431
00:36:00,436 --> 00:36:02,438
It's not permanent and so on and so forth.

432
00:36:02,458 --> 00:36:06,043
But the feeling of being the observer has a certain permanency about it.

433
00:36:07,626 --> 00:36:13,434
The feeling of being the observer has a certain steadiness about it.

434
00:36:13,454 --> 00:36:29,076
So now, when you get to that point and you really have a clear feel of being the observer, when you come out of that state into a reflection, ask yourself, what were the inner constituents of the observer?

435
00:36:33,021 --> 00:36:43,655
When there's pain in the knee, I said this to I think the small group this morning, we might go into the pain and we might find actually the noting word changes.

436
00:36:43,755 --> 00:36:51,065
It becomes tight, stingy, a lot of heat, but we don't say pain.

437
00:36:52,005 --> 00:37:01,898
When we come away from that position of observation in the pain and we come to the surface of that feeling, suddenly the word pain arises and we know that

438
00:37:02,349 --> 00:37:05,713
then that the word pain is a mental construct.

439
00:37:05,733 --> 00:37:06,934
It's not that we don't want to lose it.

440
00:37:07,016 --> 00:37:09,398
We want to know when there's pain in the body so we can go to the doctor.

441
00:37:09,878 --> 00:37:11,601
But we're not fooled by it.

442
00:37:13,043 --> 00:37:14,905
Pain doesn't exist.

443
00:37:14,985 --> 00:37:17,748
What exists are those feelings, those sensations.

444
00:37:21,733 --> 00:37:31,023
When we come out of that sense of the observer, when it's very clear to us, and you stop and you just reflect on what were the inner qualities of the observer,

445
00:37:32,302 --> 00:37:34,606
That's the first little exercise that you might do.

446
00:37:36,128 --> 00:37:37,751
The second one is more meditative.

447
00:37:38,331 --> 00:37:52,833
When you get that sense of the observer, difficult to get it in a weekend, you understand, but when you get that sense of the observer, turn to it, you see, the feel of it, the sense of presence.

448
00:37:52,853 --> 00:38:00,606
That sense of presence is often thought by people to be their soul, a sense of presence, you see.

449
00:38:01,648 --> 00:38:02,769
But it's also an object.

450
00:38:04,110 --> 00:38:04,652
It can't be you.

451
00:38:06,974 --> 00:38:11,458
The feeling of self-awareness, right?

452
00:38:11,478 --> 00:38:18,164
You're aware of the feeling or the idea of self-awareness.

453
00:38:18,865 --> 00:38:20,987
So therefore, that can't be you either.

454
00:38:23,030 --> 00:38:23,871
It's very mysterious.

455
00:38:25,251 --> 00:38:31,237
So what we do then is we put the attention just on the feel, the sense of presence.

456
00:38:31,257 --> 00:38:31,538
You see?

457
00:38:32,429 --> 00:38:43,862
And then at some point there may be some realisation or some understanding that that which is looking is what we've been looking for.

458
00:38:44,463 --> 00:38:46,407
But we'll never be able to see it.

459
00:38:48,668 --> 00:38:49,289
That's the problem.

460
00:38:50,532 --> 00:38:53,434
So in the Mahayana they talk about the eye.

461
00:38:53,695 --> 00:38:55,097
The eye can never see itself.

462
00:38:56,719 --> 00:38:57,981
The nose can't smell itself.

463
00:38:58,771 --> 00:39:00,833
The tongue cannot taste itself.

464
00:39:01,634 --> 00:39:06,518
If the basic taste of a tongue was curry, it would mess up the ice cream.

465
00:39:07,659 --> 00:39:08,840
It's the fact that it's empty.

466
00:39:08,880 --> 00:39:12,885
It doesn't have any taste that we can taste.

467
00:39:12,905 --> 00:39:15,628
It's the fact that the eye cannot see itself that it can see.

468
00:39:18,570 --> 00:39:26,719
So we can only be, we can only experience that within us which is not part of this phenomenal world.

469
00:39:28,217 --> 00:39:32,804
So now we have the Buddha trying to explain this.

470
00:39:35,467 --> 00:39:40,074
A little bit more straightforward than I'm doing.

471
00:39:41,958 --> 00:39:43,440
I'm just going to find the location here.

472
00:39:55,076 --> 00:39:55,336
Okay.

473
00:39:55,356 --> 00:39:55,456
Okay.

474
00:40:14,387 --> 00:40:15,228
Oh, sorry, wrong one.

475
00:40:16,570 --> 00:40:25,300
Try again.

476
00:40:25,320 --> 00:40:27,643
This is a very famous, often quoted.

477
00:40:27,682 --> 00:40:42,960
So, this is the point where the Buddha's talking to the

478
00:40:43,818 --> 00:40:45,981
Listeners to his audience.

479
00:40:46,541 --> 00:40:48,563
Often mixed between monks and lay people.

480
00:40:50,346 --> 00:40:52,188
And he's instructing them about the Dharma.

481
00:40:52,268 --> 00:40:53,650
Which is the teaching, the truth.

482
00:40:54,291 --> 00:40:55,373
Connected to Nibbana.

483
00:40:57,456 --> 00:40:58,836
And to those who are receptive.

484
00:40:59,358 --> 00:41:00,179
Those who have ears.

485
00:41:00,940 --> 00:41:01,601
Let them hear.

486
00:41:02,922 --> 00:41:04,925
There is an unborn.

487
00:41:05,706 --> 00:41:06,547
An unbecome.

488
00:41:07,168 --> 00:41:07,829
An unmade.

489
00:41:08,369 --> 00:41:09,351
An unconditioned.

490
00:41:10,172 --> 00:41:10,793
So there is.

491
00:41:11,233 --> 00:41:12,474
Now the word he uses.

492
00:41:12,742 --> 00:41:42,715
there are two words for is in the Pali one is hoti and it's used like a connective so if I say this is a shrine it's just a connecting word but ati, the word he uses means exists, there exists the not born he uses an adjective so he doesn't concretise it the unborn an unbecome something which isn't in a process of becoming, changing

493
00:41:43,235 --> 00:41:45,018
And unmade, uncreated.

494
00:41:45,257 --> 00:41:46,219
It was never created.

495
00:41:46,260 --> 00:41:48,985
It's not born, it's not created.

496
00:41:50,347 --> 00:41:51,568
And unconditioned.

497
00:41:52,070 --> 00:41:53,311
It's beyond conditioning.

498
00:41:54,373 --> 00:41:58,059
Conditioning only happens when there's two things there.

499
00:41:58,079 --> 00:42:05,311
So, because I'm in this room and in this way, and in this retreat, I'm being conditioned to sit in this manner.

500
00:42:06,494 --> 00:42:08,938
But this is something which is beyond all conditioning.

501
00:42:13,255 --> 00:42:27,751
If there were no unborn, no unbecome, no unmade or unconditioned, no escape could be discerned from what is born, from what does become, what is creative and what is conditioned.

502
00:42:29,052 --> 00:42:42,047
But because there is, there exists, that which is not born, doesn't die, doesn't become, is not creative and not conditioned, there is an escape to be discerned.

503
00:42:42,364 --> 00:42:43,306
From what is born.

504
00:42:43,445 --> 00:42:45,829
Become made and conditioned.

505
00:42:45,849 --> 00:42:46,530
That's pretty clear.

506
00:42:48,512 --> 00:42:49,554
But there's another passage.

507
00:42:49,594 --> 00:42:51,115
Where he's even clearer.

508
00:42:52,137 --> 00:42:53,298
Because he's asked by.

509
00:42:53,338 --> 00:42:54,900
Somebody.

510
00:42:56,282 --> 00:42:57,463
Where is it he says.

511
00:42:57,684 --> 00:43:00,108
That the four great elements.

512
00:43:00,188 --> 00:43:00,829
Come to an end.

513
00:43:01,929 --> 00:43:02,311
Complete.

514
00:43:03,592 --> 00:43:04,673
Now the four great elements.

515
00:43:05,795 --> 00:43:07,838
Are earth, fire, water and air.

516
00:43:08,257 --> 00:43:09,400
And they're symbolic for.

517
00:43:10,240 --> 00:43:10,661
Pressure.

518
00:43:11,382 --> 00:43:11,983
Gravity.

519
00:43:13,465 --> 00:43:15,268
Fire, heat, energy.

520
00:43:16,068 --> 00:43:20,335
Water, that which congeals elasticity, holds things together.

521
00:43:21,235 --> 00:43:22,056
And movement.

522
00:43:23,980 --> 00:43:26,543
It's the way the mind experiences matter.

523
00:43:26,563 --> 00:43:31,489
Not to be confused with the grand theory of physics.

524
00:43:31,510 --> 00:43:38,679
The Buddha's descriptions are always about the mind and the way it experiences the world.

525
00:43:39,706 --> 00:43:43,009
So this questioner says, where does the world come to an end?

526
00:43:43,028 --> 00:43:43,969
That's what he's saying.

527
00:43:43,989 --> 00:43:44,731
The physical world.

528
00:43:44,771 --> 00:43:48,914
And the Buddha says, the question is not put rightly.

529
00:43:49,436 --> 00:43:53,239
What you should be asking is, where does the world not find a footing?

530
00:43:55,641 --> 00:43:59,224
And he comes out with a phrase which only occurs two times in the scriptures.

531
00:44:00,326 --> 00:44:01,467
There is a consciousness.

532
00:44:02,168 --> 00:44:05,170
Now again, we've got to be careful of this word consciousness.

533
00:44:05,251 --> 00:44:09,054
I would prefer there is a knowing or there is an awareness.

534
00:44:09,271 --> 00:44:12,255
There's an awareness.

535
00:44:12,275 --> 00:44:13,456
Which is without boundary.

536
00:44:14,597 --> 00:44:16,862
Now boundary is only created by phenomena.

537
00:44:16,961 --> 00:44:18,664
It's only because we've got four walls here.

538
00:44:18,985 --> 00:44:20,907
Not this room as a boundary.

539
00:44:20,927 --> 00:44:21,748
So it's without boundary.

540
00:44:21,768 --> 00:44:22,489
There's no phenomena.

541
00:44:22,509 --> 00:44:25,813
There's nothing there in that sense.

542
00:44:25,833 --> 00:44:27,637
Not coloured by any of the senses.

543
00:44:29,498 --> 00:44:33,364
So the senses are in Buddhism the five ones that we know.

544
00:44:33,425 --> 00:44:35,907
But also the mind as a sensing base.

545
00:44:36,668 --> 00:44:38,771
Which includes our images and thoughts etc.

546
00:44:39,157 --> 00:44:45,264
So nothing is there that we would normally describe a human being by.

547
00:44:45,284 --> 00:44:47,447
And in all directions, full of light.

548
00:44:48,869 --> 00:44:50,610
And awakenedness.

549
00:44:50,630 --> 00:44:55,157
Just this is the end of suffering.

550
00:44:55,177 --> 00:44:59,081
So now, our job is to find what that is.

551
00:44:59,822 --> 00:45:04,168
When we say find what that is, it means direct experience for ourselves.

552
00:45:05,228 --> 00:45:06,971
And the process is one of negation.

553
00:45:07,512 --> 00:45:08,572
Not me, not mine.

554
00:45:09,768 --> 00:45:27,547
So in your meditation sometimes you might sit down and just say to yourself, well, in this particular practice, this quarter of an hour, an hour, whatever you want to take, I'm just going to point to things as they come up and I'm just going to say, there.

555
00:45:28,768 --> 00:45:35,175
So there's pain, there's comfort, there's joy, there's a thought, there, there, there, all the time.

556
00:45:35,195 --> 00:45:38,880
And when you get to that sense of self, there's a sense of self, there, there.

557
00:45:39,755 --> 00:46:09,541
constantly pulling yourself out of this enmeshment this enchantment with the psychophysical organism and there is no doubt that within good time insights will arise which will liberate us from our delusions so what is the delusion that the Buddha talks about what is this essential delusion it's a delusion about who we are

558
00:46:11,766 --> 00:46:18,916
And the deeper process of our meditation, of our practice, is to find out what it is that we really are.

559
00:46:20,217 --> 00:46:22,481
To put it in a very positive way.

560
00:46:25,085 --> 00:46:28,909
So, we've talked about these five khandhas.

561
00:46:29,210 --> 00:46:31,052
The body, feelings.

562
00:46:32,034 --> 00:46:34,016
Khandhas here means aggregates, heaps.

563
00:46:34,577 --> 00:46:35,338
They're all different.

564
00:46:35,998 --> 00:46:37,780
The body, sensations, feelings.

565
00:46:39,222 --> 00:46:40,525
Feelings in the body.

566
00:46:41,197 --> 00:47:09,786
our perceptions and conceptions all our habits that are made by will and therefore can be unmade and this is where the suffering is to distinguish between suffering and pain so pain in the knee is just pain what we make of it is the suffering our aversion and fear of it and finally acts of cognition and each time he's asking always is this permanent does this

567
00:47:10,052 --> 00:47:13,396
Can this be defined as a soul, an eternal soul?

568
00:47:14,818 --> 00:47:16,942
And then he talks about impermanence.

569
00:47:16,961 --> 00:47:22,248
And because things are impermanent, they have an inbuilt suffering because they can't satisfy.

570
00:47:23,050 --> 00:47:24,492
And that's the meaning of dukkha.

571
00:47:25,213 --> 00:47:27,456
Dukkha is a core word in the Buddha's language.

572
00:47:28,036 --> 00:47:33,063
We translate it as unsatisfactoriness, as suffering, a sense of lack, a sense of incompleteness.

573
00:47:34,184 --> 00:47:37,849
It's always there, even though we might have ecstatic moments.

574
00:47:38,521 --> 00:47:39,762
it always passes.

575
00:47:39,981 --> 00:47:44,246
So there's always a sense of... And you know you can't get that again.

576
00:47:44,887 --> 00:47:50,152
It's a disaster, isn't it, when you have a great party and you say, let's have another one.

577
00:47:50,172 --> 00:47:51,112
But you just don't do that.

578
00:47:53,675 --> 00:48:06,266
And then we talked about this more modern way of looking at the way our sense of self retreats out of the world into a sense of me, the person,

579
00:48:06,905 --> 00:48:10,150
And how the meditation is just taking that inward.

580
00:48:11,472 --> 00:48:18,641
And eventually of course what we realise is that the outer world and the inner world are all being manufactured by the mind.

581
00:48:20,344 --> 00:48:26,873
We live in this bubble of consciousness which we are actually manufacturing moment after moment.

582
00:48:26,893 --> 00:48:29,297
So in a sense what we make of it is our own problem.

583
00:48:31,922 --> 00:48:35,427
And then finally statements which point to

584
00:48:35,726 --> 00:49:01,869
something in us which is doesn't belong to this realm of phenomena this realm of the sense world and a little couple of exercises which might take us there that being able to label things being able to point to things and say well there there it is so you're always creating a distinction between the object and the one that knows the one who knows

585
00:49:04,110 --> 00:49:15,369
And that other final thing, that when we become very clear about the sense of the observer, as distinct from everything that's happening, the reflection afterwards, what's it made of?

586
00:49:15,570 --> 00:49:18,675
What was inside this observer?

587
00:49:20,880 --> 00:49:22,262
Okay?

588
00:49:22,282 --> 00:49:24,164
I expect an answer by noon tomorrow.

589
00:49:27,391 --> 00:49:28,211
I'll give you marks.

590
00:49:31,364 --> 00:49:34,108
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

591
00:49:34,608 --> 00:49:46,505
May you by your clarity and devotion to the practice be liberated from all delusion and suffering sooner rather than later.

592
00:49:46,525 --> 00:49:47,786
You're supposed to say sad.

593
00:49:50,670 --> 00:49:53,855
If you don't say that, I'll go away feeling God.

594
00:49:54,275 --> 00:49:56,038
It's been terrible.

